ard.com/utmayes1999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 84<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/23/02 12:21:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   space junk removal</span><hr size=1> Star wars is the solution to the space junk problem in leo.<br>
The answer is to use high energy lasers to remove stuff<br>
from leo by heating it up and evaporating it. It takes<br>
7500 watts of laser power to heat up 1 gram of mass to<br>
3000 celcius. This will vaporize the 1 gram of mass by turning<br>
it into a ball of plasma gas. A 75 kw laser beam  can vaporize<br>
10 grams of mass with a one second pulse. It can vaporize<br>
600 grams of mass if the laser focus on an obeject in leo for <br>
1 minute. If I were to put a 1.5 megawatt laser in leo I<br>
can vaporize 200 grams of mass with a 1 second laser pulse.<br>
In ten seconds I could vaporize 2000 grams of mass which is<br>
2 kilograms. In 60 seconds  which is 1 minute I can vaporize<br>
12 kilograms of mass with such a laser beam. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/utmayes1999.showPublicProfile?language=EN>tmayes1999</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 85<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/23/02 12:26:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: space junk removal</span><hr size=1> If I use a 1.5 gigawat laser beam I could vaporize 200,000<br>
grams of mass in a 1 second laser pulse. This is 200 kilograms of mass. If I fire the 1.5 gw  laser for 1 minute (60 seconds )<br>
 at an leo object I can literaly  vaporize 12,000 kilograms of mass in leo in 60 seconds.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=x>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 33<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/25/02 8:25:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: space junk removal</span><hr size=1> For once, the environmentalists are right, we should recycle.  I'm not talking about the iddy bitty pieces that are less than 10 cm in diameter.  I'm talking about salvaging old satellites and upper stage boosters.  Hey!  Think of it as <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Sanford and Son</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> in space <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   There have been Mars Society conference talks on using the aluminum in space junk for solid fuel.  And I read an article in a magazine from the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Artimus Society</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> for using space junk as mass for tethers since a tether must have many times more mass than the cargo it's taking a hold of unless it loses too much momentum in placing cargos in higher orbits. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 214<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/25/02 8:44:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: space junk removal</span><hr size=1> One serious problem with salvaging those items are that they may be explosive.<br>
<br>
Yale <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=x>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 35<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/25/02 9:02:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: space junk removal</span><hr size=1> Not to mention the hard vacuum, deadly radiation, bone and muscle apathy caused by long exposure to microgravity.  But hey, as Q said, &quot;It's not safe out here! It's wondrous, with treasures to satiate desires both subtle and gross. But it's not for the timid.&quot; <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 217<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/25/02 9:15:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~nuclearspace/ezboard/images/posticons/radman.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: space junk removal</span><hr size=1> Its one thing to bravely face the inevitable rain of high energy protons. It is another thing to deliberately approach a derelict Agena upper stage. E-mail NASA and ask them if they think that is a type of risk that they would ever consider worth taking.<br>
yale <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=x>X</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 38<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/25/02 9:37:52 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: space junk removal</span><hr size=1> I don't see a difference between the two.  Both are risks.  Besides, I seem to recall there quite a lot of fuel between an astronaut and the ground and I don't see them complaining. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uyales.showPublicProfile?language=EN>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NERVA Spaceplane Pilot</span><br>  Posts: 219<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(4/25/02 9:58:32 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm25.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=77.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: space junk removal</span><hr size=1> You're missing my point. There are risks you MUST take, and there are optional risks that may fall off the risk/benefit scale.<br>
<br>
Thus NASA abandoned the LH2/LOX booster for space probes that was designed for the shuttle bay. NASA had to delay Galileo and redesign the mission to boost Galileo with a lower energy kickstage and use grav sling shots and plus extra years transit time to get to Jupiter.<br>
<br>
Yet the Shuttle main engines are LH2/LOX. This risk is unavoidable, while the kickstage was optional.<br>
<br>
NASA never rests tho, the main engines are always under redevelopment to lower their hazard and up their reliability.<br>
<br>
